<subSubSection pageId="666" pageNumber="667" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph pageId="666" pageNumber="667">
Subgenus 
<taxonomicName LSID="6B9B4FC4-682E-52B9-A1B5-AE3F1B16C80B" authority="Motschulsky, 1864" authorityName="Motschulsky" authorityYear="1864" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Psychristus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="(Liocellus)" order="Coleoptera" pageId="666" pageNumber="667" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Liocellus">Liocellus Motschulsky, 1864</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="666" pageNumber="667" type="reference_group">
<paragraph pageId="666" pageNumber="667">
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Liocellus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="666" pageNumber="667" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Liocellus</taxonomicName>
Motschulsky, 1864: 207. Type species: 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Stephens" baseAuthorityYear="1835" class="Hexapoda" family="Carabidae" genus="Acupalpus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="666" pageNumber="667" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nitidus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="666" pageNumber="667">Acupalpus nitidus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Dejean, 1829 designated by Lindroth (1968: 882). Etymology. From the Greek prefix 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="666" pageNumber="667">lio</emphasis>
- (smooth) and 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="666" pageNumber="667">cello</emphasis>
(to run) [masculine].
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="666" pageNumber="667">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Casey" authorityYear="1885" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Glycerius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="666" pageNumber="667" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Glycerius</taxonomicName>
Casey, 1884c: 79. Type species: 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Stephens" baseAuthorityYear="1835" class="Hexapoda" family="Carabidae" genus="Acupalpus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="666" pageNumber="667" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nitidus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="666" pageNumber="667">Acupalpus nitidus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Dejean, 1829 by monotypy. Etymology. Possibly from the Greek 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="666" pageNumber="667">glyceros</emphasis>
(sweet) [masculine].
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="666" pageNumber="667" type="diversity">
<paragraph pageId="666" pageNumber="667">Diversity.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="666" pageNumber="667">Eight species in North America (seven species) and Mexico (one species).</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="666" pageNumber="667" type="identification">
<paragraph pageId="666" pageNumber="667">Identification.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="666" pageNumber="667">
Fall (1905: 175, as 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Casey" authorityYear="1885" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Glycerius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="666" pageNumber="667" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="666" pageNumber="667">Glycerius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) published a key to the four North American species then known. Casey (1924) subsequently added three new species. The subgenus is in need of a taxonomic revision.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
